name: PluralAndGenderVisitor
comment: A visitor to extract information from Intl.plural/gender sends. Note that this is a SimpleASTVisitor, so it doesn't automatically recurse. So this needs to be called where we expect a plural or gender immediately below.

parent.name: parent
parent.comment: A plural or gender always exists in the context of a parent message, which could in turn also be a plural or gender.

pieces.name: pieces
pieces.comment: The pieces of the message. We are given an initial version of this from our parent and we add to it as we find additional information.

foundPluralOrGender.name: foundPluralOrGender
foundPluralOrGender.comment: This will be set to true if we find a plural or gender.

looksLikePluralOrGender.name: looksLikePluralOrGender
looksLikePluralOrGender.comment: Return true if intl/extract_messages.PluralAndGenderVisitor.looksLikePluralOrGender.node matches the pattern for plural or gender message.

checkValidity.name: checkValidity
checkValidity.comment: Returns a String describing why the node is invalid, or null if no reason is found, so it's presumed valid.

messageFromMethodInvocation.name: messageFromMethodInvocation
messageFromMethodInvocation.comment: Create a MainMessage from intl/extract_messages.PluralAndGenderVisitor.messageFromMethodInvocation.node using the name and parameters of the last function/method declaration we encountered e and the parameters to the Intl.message call.

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides intl/extract_messages.PluralAndGenderVisitor.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

runtimeType.name: runtimeType
runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and intl/extract_messages.PluralAndGenderVisitor.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the intl/extract_messages.PluralAndGenderVisitor.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
intl/extract_messages.PluralAndGenderVisitor.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to intl/extract_messages.PluralAndGenderVisitor.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If intl/extract_messages.PluralAndGenderVisitor.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of intl/extract_messages.PluralAndGenderVisitor.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.
